# 📦 SUMMARY  
# This code builds: A short interactive session inside a Docker container to inspect and change permissions on the Docker socket file.  
# Language/Platform: Bash (Linux) + PowerShell equivalents provided  
# What you'll learn: Running commands inside a container, inspecting file permissions, modifying permissions with chmod.  
# Outcome: The Docker socket file (/var/run/docker.sock) inside the container will have its permissions updated.  
# Why this matters: Changing permissions on docker.sock allows non-root users or processes inside the container to interact with the Docker daemon, which is often needed in CI/CD workflows or development environments.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 START INTERACTIVE SHELL IN CONTAINER  
# ------------------------------  
docker exec -u 0 -it 3b8206735dcf bash  
# ✅ What it does: Starts an interactive shell session (`bash`) inside the container with ID `3b8206735dcf` as the root user (`-u 0`).  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Allows us to execute commands inside the container with root privileges. This is required for changing file permissions.  
# 🔄 PowerShell equivalent:  
# docker exec -u 0 -it 3b8206735dcf powershell  
# ✅ What it does: Opens a PowerShell session instead of Bash if you're working in a Windows container.  

# ------------------------------  
# ⚙️ CHECK CURRENT PERMISSIONS OF DOCKER SOCKET  
# ------------------------------  
ls -l /var/run/docker.sock  
# ✅ What it does: Lists the detailed file permissions and ownership of `/var/run/docker.sock` inside the container.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Shows who can currently read/write to the Docker socket. By default, it might be owned by `root` and only accessible to users in the `docker` group.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🛠️ MODIFY PERMISSIONS ON DOCKER SOCKET  
# ------------------------------  
chmod 666 /var/run/docker.sock  
# ✅ What it does: Changes the file permissions so that **all users (owner, group, others)** can read and write to `/var/run/docker.sock`.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: This allows non-root users and processes inside the container to communicate with the Docker daemon. Be careful: this grants broad access and could be a security risk.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🔁 VERIFY UPDATED PERMISSIONS  
# ------------------------------  
ls -l /var/run/docker.sock  
# ✅ What it does: Lists the file permissions again to confirm that they have been updated to `-rw-rw-rw-` (read/write for everyone).  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Double-checking ensures the `chmod` command worked as expected.  

# ------------------------------  
# ⏹️ EXIT CONTAINER SHELL  
# ------------------------------  
exit  
# ✅ What it does: Exits the interactive shell session inside the container and returns you to the host system shell.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Closes the container session cleanly once changes are applied.  

# ------------------------------  
# ▶️ HOW TO RUN / EXECUTE THIS CODE  
# ------------------------------  
# ✅ Step 1: Copy the container ID from `docker ps` if needed  
# docker ps                          # Lists all running containers with IDs and names  
# 🔄 PowerShell equivalent:  
# docker ps                          # Same command works in PowerShell  

# ✅ Step 2: Run the commands above step by step inside the container  
# 🔄 PowerShell alternative inside Windows container:  
# Replace `bash` with `powershell` in the `docker exec` command  

# ------------------------------  
# ✅ NOTES / GOTCHAS / TIPS  
# ------------------------------  
# - Granting 666 permissions to docker.sock allows any process in the container to control Docker. Only do this in **trusted environments**.  
# - For production setups, consider adding users to the `docker` group instead of using `chmod 666`.  
# - If you’re working in Windows containers, replace `bash` with `cmd` or `powershell`.  
# - To avoid running as root, use `docker exec -it --user <username>` if a user exists in the container.  
